AGI - On 4 May Renato Vallanzasca was 74 years old, of which the last 52 almost all spent in prison. "We went to wish him luck. He was embarrassed, stunned by illness and drugs," tells AGI who met him in the Bollate prison where he is serving four life sentences for robberies, murders and kidnappings. Friends don't miss the old bandit in Milan in the 1970s. Like Tino Stefanini, who was part of his gang and in October will end up serving half a century of jail even if he has already been in custody for some time.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Renato is sick, terrible. It has a few moments of clarity. Who goes to interview with him tells me that the degenerative disease he suffers advances. What are they waiting to get him out? His name remains. The first signs I saw them four years ago, forgot to come and eat." After a life on the road, the two spent many years together also in cell. "We did the air together, I love him. I'm sick to know that." The next few weeks will be decisive for his future after the Supervisory Court revoked his permissions in recent months to go to therapeutic communities at least once a week, claiming that he can receive adequate care for Bollates.
&nbsp;
"On June 19, we will discuss the complaint against this decision - explains to AGI lawyer Paolo Muzzi who assists him with his colleague Corrado Limentani -. Vallanzasca has never given problems in that context, he has always used permits correctly and punctually. Then we will present an application to have domiciles on the basis of medical documents in possession of the same prison that certify its disease. In the meantime we have asked for the appointment of a support administrator and are waiting for the judge to protect us who will have to take care of him. The world of Vallanzasca ended 40 years ago and after 52 years in prison we can say that the State has won, it does not need to deny it the opportunity to cure itself at best."
&nbsp;
"It is not enough that the lesser physical infirmity, also relevant, the health of the condemned and is susceptible to generic improvement outside the prison but it is necessary that the infirmity be of such gravity to make the expiation of the detention penalty appear in contrast with the sense of humanity to which the constitutional and supranational dictates are inspired" wrote the Cassation when rejected in November 2023 the use of defence &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The doctors of Opera, where he was previously recruited, had spoken of "slow cognitive decay". "We would like to have an insight into his condition that has been denied to us in the past because &nbsp; the situation is getting worse and worse," the defenders say. The Cassation has always made it clear that the existence of a "cognitive deteration" is undeniable, but, in fact, it has not assessed it incompatible with the dignity of the prisoner. Those who have seen him describe him as "closed in his world, empty" and believes that in prison he cannot receive adequate stimuli to slow down the darkness that is invading his mind.&nbsp;

